 that the Revolution was still being shaped as late as 1820 and that many racial, territorial, economic, and constitutional issues were submerged in the growth of the republic and the enthusiasm of the population. In addressing the nature of the Revolution, Nellis suggests that the American Revolution and American political systems and principles are unique and much less suited for export than many Americans believe.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jul 2022) 0aDemocracyzUnited StatesxHistory. 4aCoursebook. 7aHISTORY / United States / Revolutionary Period (1775-1800).2bisacsh  aAmerican Revolution.  aAmerican political system.  aBritish imperial policies.  aconstitutional.  aeconomic.  agrowth of the republic.  aindependence.  aissues.  aprinciples.  apublic enthusiasm.  aracial.  aterritorial.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311049095440uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978144260331840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781442603318423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781442603318/original  a978-3-11-049095-4  University of Toronto Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK